Of the new patients, CS Kagwe said in a statement, Kenyans numbered 221 and foreigners nine, whereas the oldest was 77 and the youngest two.










Nairobi County accounted for 77 of the new cases, Taita Taveta 36, Kiambu 20, Busia 19, Kisumu 12, Meru 11, and Uasin Gishu and Kilifi 10 each.
Then came Kitui wuth nine Mombasa and Kajiado with four each, Laikipia and Murang’a with three each, Nakuru with two, and Kisii, Machakos, Garissa, Trans Nzoia, Bungoma, Nyamira, Migori, Makueni, Siaya and Vihiga with one each.





One more death
As was the case on Friday, the ministry announced just one more death, raising the toll to 1,703.
Mr Kagwe further said 137 more patients had recovered from the disease, 127 under the home-based care programme and 10 at various hospitals, raising the number to 80,808.










New Content Item (1)


The Ministry of Health said that as of Saturday, 664 patients had been admitted countywide while 1,961 were under home-based isolation and care.
Thirty one patients were under intensive care, 20 of them on ventilatory support, 11 on supplemental oxygen and one under observation.
Another 10 patients were also on supplemental oxygen but in the general wards, the CS said, adding no patient was in a high dependency unit.



